element_texts.text: Completed

Sam C. Jennings
Moravia, Cayuga County
N. York
Completed

1849 March 21st Wednesday
Left home and its dear ones Monday March 19th 1849. The parting scene can be imagined, not described, & as I turned to take a last fond look, at my own dear home, and all that earth held dear, tears unbidden dimmed my eyes. Mans stern nature melted into childhood, & we journeyed on in sadness & in silence, took dinner at Dr. Whites & reached Ithica in the evening. Spent one day in Ithica (20th) making preparations for our journey across the Prairies we were all armed with rifles = revolvers = & large knives Our dress was of sheeps grey cloth, ¶ hide brimmed hats protected us from rain & sun. at first I did not think of joining the Company formed in Ithica, but, from the representations of the secretary (which afterwards proved false) I was induced to join in the evening a upper was given to us by the citizens, & Wednesday March 21st escorted by a band of music & hundreds of the citizens of Ithica, the Ithica & Auburn Compound? marched in procession to the cars?. When all were slated? we were addressed by Mr. Cushing in a very appropriate & touching manner/ and during the adress many a sun burnt cheek was wet with tears. Dr. White replied to Mr. Cushing then came the parting scene, and as the car moved on, the cheering of the multitude drowned
Completed

the low sad farewell of parting friends and our long, long journey was commenced. & many perhaps of our little band would never retrace their steps the road between Ithica & Oswego is very poor & the cars were drawn by horses, the country is hilly = with excellent forests of pine. Took dinner at the Halfway House & soon after it commenced raining and snowing together, & continued all night. We reached Oswego (29 miles distance) about 5 P.M. & were received with firing of cannon. There were here two Rafts & an Ark in waiting to carry us down the river, provided by Mr. Miles contractor for the transportation of the company to Independence. We found temporary shelters & straw to sleep upon, & plowed? down the river about two or three miles on account of the floating ice, & tying up, passed a very uncomfortable night, many went on shore to a pubic house, & found lodgings (22nd M) lay by today, the river being very high, called on Mr. Seneca Dennis Oswego, took dinner at his house
23rd started about 6 A.M. & upon calling the roll found one of our men Mr. Kemball absent, passed between mountains either side, the river in the summer is shallow, about twenty miles from Oswego we were overtaken by Mr. Kemball we gave three cheers & threw our raft near shore for him to jump on, in which he proceeded, we passed a number of little villages in the forenoon. the largest of which was Howards?
Completed

The scenery along the banks of the river is very romantic. Travelled about 65 miles, & fastened our rafts for the night, as it would have been dangerous running in the dark. about midnight we were awakened by another raft running into us, & breaking our raft apart, but they were fortunately secured again soon after the raft that run into us, was broken loose by another radt, coming down, which threw it into the current of the river, to float down & run the risk of breaking to peices on some of the numerous Islands in the darkness of the night.
March 24th (Saturday) Started early in the morning, the day was very pleasant, soon after dinner we entered the Wyoming Valley which is a very pretty valley 4 or 5 miles wide, we saw the monument erected in memory of those who fell in the savage Massacre in    in the afternoon passed the village of Wilkesbarre, we fired a salute as we passed, & were cheered by the inhabitants in return, so far there has been much boisterous merriment which was checked by a sad accident, we had floated down the river thus far, two rafts abreast. there was now a "shute" to run, through a dam about 10 ft high and a considerable fall below, and only wide enough for one raft at a time we therefore seperated our rafts, our raft taking the
Completed

lead with inexperienced hands at the Cars?, by much exertion we entered the raft straight, and it flew down the rapids like a frightened bird, and through the swells below.  As the swells went over our raft, some light baggage was washed overboard, but we caught it as  we passed, and saved it.  the Ark passed through next, in safety, & we waited anxiously for the remaining raft, upon which was the pilot, many of our men taking passage on this raft, thinking it safe in the pilots hands, & upon it too, was most of our luggage.  soon we hear shouting for help.  the men on the Ark pointing in the direction of the Shute we immediatley blew up an India Rubber boat on our raft & I jumped in followed by two others.  we rowed up the river as fast as we could, when the Irons for the oars came off, & we used the oars as paddles, till we reached the Art, when others jumped in and pulled for the shore, the river being so rapid, that the boat would not ascend.  soon after the raft came through broken to peices, & we heard the melancholy story of the loss of  of one of the members of the Auburn Company a Mr John Gates, by drowning, and about two Hundred Dollars worth of property (luggage),.  the pilot ran too far out in the river, and struck the outside corer of the shute and the raft commenced swinging round towards the falls, but by great exertion
Completed

it was thrown back towards the shore. when most of the men reached the shore by jumping - wading & swimming, Mr. Gates jumped in the river, as the raft broke in peices, with his rifle in one hand, & swam for the shore, & nearly reached the corner of the shute, when the current proved too strong, and drew him into the rapids, he went down, and when last seen still grasped his rifle, the broken peices of the raft were collected together a few miles below the rapids & we lay by, to repair our broken craft, Made 70 miles
25th Sunday one of our men Mr John Phelps in jumping from the broken raft, jumped on the abutment next the dam, and was obliged to stay all night, in the morning, he was rescued from his unpleasant situation by another raft. lay by today repairing our raft, & waiting for our ? (rainy day)
26th Monday resumed our journey, the morning was pleasant but cold with some frost?, the country rough & Mountains with occasional Coal Mines, passed a number of small villages & reached Northumberland at the junction of the East & West branches of the Susquehannah about (60 Miles)
5 P.M. some of our men went into the town and had some difficulty with some of the Inhabitants. Mr. Thorn? was knocked down
Completed

We were fearful that an attempt would be made in the night to cut out raft loose, & we stationed a strong guard to prevent it, & was on guard two hours, the night was very cold. Tuesday = 27th the wind blows very hard - both branches are very high, the Auburn Company refuse to proceed any farther on the raft or run the risk of loosing life & property by passing another shute. Mr. Miles, our contractor has therefore gone to Juniatta to charter a Canal Boat to take us to Pittsburgh. We visited the town, it has the appearance of a very old place, and many of the houses are built in the dutch style, Passed another cold & stormy night on board our raft
Wednesday 28th Stormy & cold. Each man his own cook, & at night wet straw to lie upon.
Thursday 29th dropped out rafts down opposite the town. Mr. Miles returned unsuccessful in engaging a boat at Juniatta, & a Coal Boat was engaged here our things Baggage was put on board & about noon we were again under weigh. the day was pleasant, the spring being a number of days in advance of the same in the lake county of the Empire State. the grass was beginning to start & the wheat crops looked well There was no convenience for cooking a few crackers and cold meat, proposed? our supper, & the night was passed very unpleasantly, sleeping
Completed

as best we could on Boxes = Bags = Stoves = Beams = Barrels etc. etc. & the night was quite cold. = 
About daylight of the 30th reached a small place called Benvenue 42 miles distant from Northumberland about 25? of our Company myself included boarded with a widow lady a Mrs Duncan & our accomodations today contracting strangely with our situation a few hours previous, we here found all the substantial as well as ? of the season. the Island upon which stands the alone village is called Duncan's Island we spent the day in rambling about & practicing with our rifles
31st Saturday loaded our baggage on another boat & as we moved off gave three cheers & resumed our journey, as we passed the Mansion of Mrs Duncan, she appeared at the window waving her handkercheif, she was answered by three hearty cheers, this night spent very uncomfortably as usual on Boxes Bags etc many of the men are dissatisfied with our contractors arrangements
April 1st Sunday lay by at the Villiage of Mifflin the day was pleasant with chilly wind
April 2nd Monday resumed our journey the day very pleasant, the night passed more uncomfortable than usual. The reason of my being quite unwell and having a severe headache. the night seemed tediously long
Completed

Apl 3rd Tuesday.  day passed as usual.  the canal is situated on the Banks of the Juniatta & frequently the bed of the river is used as a canal.  about noon passed some curious shaped rocks one. resembling a church steeple, another a miniature chinese wall some 20 ft high 2 or 3 ft thick and about 100 yds long. reached Holidaysburg  about 1/2 past 9 oclock in the evening went to a Public House & once more slept comfortably
4th. the Canal terminating here we took the Cars over the Alleghay Mountains. there were five inclined planes? each ?, & the Cars were drawn up by stationary engines.  the inclined planes? were from 1/2 to 1 & 1/4 miles in length.  the cars being delayed on the top of the mountain I visited a coal mine which are numerous in this neighborhood.  the coal was drawn out by steam.  our road today has been on the edge of precipices, and over ravines.  and over these mountains Canal Boats & their loads are taken, with ease & deposited in the canal on the opposite side of the mountains we was let down the mountain by stationary engines on the western side, passed through a tunnel about a quarter of a mile in length & reached Johnstown a dirty looking place in the evening & found rather poor accomodations for the night.
Apl 5th  our contractor here.  was obliged to furnish two boats in place of one the companies refusing
Completed

to proceed any farther crowded as they had been Today there was a rumour that the cholera was in Pittsburg, & along the Ohio & Mississippi Rivers upon a meeting being called Dr Morse = Dr Briggs & myself were appointed a board of health, to take such measures as should be deemed necessary to guard against the approach of the cholera. Tonight we had rather more room, but it was still very unpleasant
Apl 6th Today a musical society was formed & a few books purchased = as also a Teraphine ^ the 7th? at Pittsburg = reached Pittsburg about 11 o'clock in the night. Passed the night on the boat
7th Apl had the pleasure here of hearing from home & found that the Auburn Company had anticipated the contractor in his arrangements & engaged a steamer and already started. Pittsburg is well called the Iron City, the Buildings are blackened by the coal dust & smoke from a thousand fires of mineral coal, & many that would otherwise appear beautiful look dirty & repulsive, stained as they are. the streets are many of them narrow & dirty. left Pittsburg about 11 o'clock in (the Steamer Cambria) in the evening.  the river here is about 1/4 to 1/2 mile wide = 
Sunday 8th Passed Wheeling. Had a discourse & singing, the river is at a good height for small steamers. the banks
Completed

on both sides look beautiful peach trees are in bloom & forest trees begin to leave out.
9th Apl Passed Portsmouth? & reached Cincinatti about 4 P.M. we here found the "Brooklyn" with the Auburn Company,, our steamer was about 40 horses making 500 miles. we were cheered by the Inhabitants. found a large company of Californians from Washington City, gave them three cheers, which were returned, & we here found Dr White who by mistake took another boat a Pittsburg 
Tuesday 11th after Breakfast took a stroll with Mr Jewell through the city & afterwards took the ferry boat & crossed over into Covington Kentucky where were some very pretty private buildings & residences. Cincinatti is well called the "Queen City of the West" there are some very pretty buildings & most of the streets are wide & clean below the city are many pretty country seats & extensive vinyards, we left Cincinatti about 7 o'clock in the evening
11th Passed Louisville which is quite a large city stopped here to take a pilot, to run the rapids a short distance below the city, which are somewhat dangerous our boat trembled in the rushing waters, but she passed through in safety, we had considerable sport here as on the Susquehannah in shooting at wild ducks, the boys were all so eager to have the first shot, that they would shoot 1/2 a mile, & it was seldom that game was killed by our too eager
Completed

sportsmen. 12th this morning passed the South America, a fast Boat, after a hard race, which came near ending in bloodshed. the South America finding, she would be passed, run into us, & tried to sun us aground, breaking our guard in & injuring our boat. the Capt took a gun & threatened to shoot the Pilot of South America if they ran into us again, & at the same time the deck hands stripped for a fight. Passed a pretty village Mt Vernon & another called Paducah,, passed also a "cave in the rock" formerly a famous retreat for robbers. the trees are here leaves out. about 9 o'clock we reached the mouth of the Ohio & entered the still muddier waters of the Mississippi. we had need the water of the Ohio for drinking, but the water now found in our tumblers at dinner looked as if taken from some mud puddle. those however whoa re acustomed to its use think it the best water in the world. on others it generally acts as a cathartic.
13th Steaming up the Mississippi with a beautiful country on either side, and with low sandy shores, arrived at St. Louis about 10 o'clock at night
14th spent the day in rambling about the city it is some place back from the river very pretty, the business part of the city is
